Key drivers include:
weak regulatory systems: insufficient regulatory oversight, lack of enforcement, punitive actions to deter offenders and inadequate inspection mechanisms;
supply chain complexity: long and complex supply chains with multiple intermediaries increase the risk of product tampering and substitution;
lack of access to affordable medicines: elevated prices and limited access to authentic medicines compel consumers to seek more affordable alternatives, often from unregulated and potentially unsafe sources (informal markets, online);
consumer awareness and education: lack of awareness among consumers about the risks of substandard and falsified medical products and how to identify them; and
